		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> DPC Toronto, eh?<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.97)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045'>Patrick "Patrick M. S" Sullivan</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11045&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> November 13, 2003</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> DPC Toronto<br />
<br />
Pre-Tourney Jank<br />
<br />
Well I figured it’s a bit of a slow week at work and all, so what the heck, I might as well hunker down and write up a tournament report for the DPC being held in Toronto, Ontario. This will be my second DPC I’m attending (the other was in Spokane) and if I have half as much fun at this one that I had in Spokane, then it’ll be well worth the measly 5-hour drive. <br />
<br />
Joining me on this wonderful expedition will be Patrick Malboeuf and Dominic Gaudreault. David Malboeuf might also be joining us (but has not confirmed at this point). The four of us had such a great time in Indianapolis that we figured we’d do it again. So far, the plan is to leave Friday morning at 9am so that we can get there in time to get our acts together and attend the 6pm warm-up standard tourney held in a convenience store somewhere on Yonge street. <br />
<br />
I’m actually looking forward to the ROTK Sealed Deck event Saturday night more than the actual Standard Format cash tournament. I’m really looking forward to the new site path to redefine what Standard Format is all about. I like that there is so much variety in Standard compared to Open, but I still feel like I’ve been seeing the same decks for quite some time now. I think ROTK will really spice things up. <br />
<br />
After writing my article for the DGMA on the World Cup, I figured I’d build the deck I was talking about that I’d bring if I went to the World Cup. It’s pure-Rohan with Uruk Trackers, Saruman and Lurtz. My Rohan races to nine like the wind (except against Moria where I need to be a little quiet) and my shadow should be able to stop really well or at least devastate a fool hardy double move. It’s also the same type of deck I’ve tried building Online with tons of commons and uncommons so I’m used to it by now. I won’t bother with a decklist since I plan on dismantling the deck (along with my open format deck) as soon as I get home from the DPC, never to be played again.<br />
<br />
It hit me just this week that Open format and Standard Format as we know it will cease to exist. At least when Two Towers came out, Fellowship decks were conserved to their own format: Fellowship Block. But this time, there is no format to conserve Open and Standard decks with Two Towers site paths. I’ll miss those formats but I’m pretty sick of both of them. I like to have the occasional game of Fellowship or Towers Block (and will always keep a deck of both handy) but in the meantime, I’m going to focus my energy on making a new Standard deck. I have no idea where I should start. I have some experience with the Sauron ROTK shadow from playtesting online but I am really curious to try out Southrons. <br />
<br />
Anyway, I have no real idea what Dominic or David might be bringing but Patrick seems to be hinting that he’s bringing a tentacle/southron swarm deck. I don’t believe him entirely but I would be really happy if he did bring that type of deck. It would certainly make for some pretty humiliating defeats J<br />
<br />
Friday, November 7th, 2003 <br />
‘ah, frimbazel’<br />
<br />
So I get up around 7 or so and make some coffee. Wendy has to go to work (I feel so bad) but I just laze around and open up some ROTK packs waiting for the boys to show up. Dom and Pat show up almost on time for once (thanks to Dom, I’m sure). No Dave Malboeuf though L   that’s too bad.<br />
<br />
So we take off to Toronto and stop at Pizza Hut to try the lunch buffet around 11h30. Not too shabby. That cinnamon apple desert pizza isn’t exactly the best thing I’ve ever eaten but everything else was killer. It seemed to have a real effect on the digestive systems of Pat and Dom and the next few hours in the car were not a picnic. The windows were rolled open and closed on the hour every hour. It was pretty gross. I know that I had to plan my revenge at some point later this weekend. <br />
<br />
We end up arriving in the convenience store where the tournament will be held around 3pm (way too early). So I disappear and have a pint of StrongBow at some really non-authentic local pub (Mick E. Finn’s, I believe). That gets my mood in the right place and then I head back to the store where Pat and Dom are playtesting Standard format with Towers site path for the last time. We get a little hungry and drop by the local Quizno’s before the tournament. Best sub place ever. <br />
<br />
Then upon re-entering 401 Convenience, I spot a new Wizards of the Coast CCG by the name of Neopets. My gf, Wendy, is hugely addicted to the NeoPets franchise so I pick up a starter kit. I still haven’t tried it but it looks really REALLY bad so far.  First of all, there are dice (so right away you know the skill level will be really high compared to the luck factor), but in the rules, if ever you roll a six (on a six-sided die) you automatically win the ‘contest’ no matter how much your opponent’s neopet out-matches yours. How dumb is that? Anyway at the same time, I really can’t wait to build my first neopet deck J<br />
<br />
So there is a Magic tournament downstairs so we have to place in the 3rd floor attic whose Air Conditioning unit has a vent that is permanently open all the time and it is FREEZING outside. So luckily there is no break and we’ll just try to get thru the first four rounds as fast as possible. There is a great turnout for Josh’s warm-up event and I’m really happy to see that Brad Eire showed up for the event. The Syracuse guys still aren’t here and I later find out that they gave ambigious directions to their cab who drove them to the other end of town for no reason so they showed up by round three, too late to join in. Tubman shows up after the first round and takes a game loss in order to play. Wicked.<br />
<br />
So Josh announces first round pairings and…<br />
<br />
Round One<br />
Brad Eire with his outwounding Nazgul shadow<br />
Result: FW shadow kill site 5<br />
Good: Brad is the best, I can’t believe I had such a tough first round match up but I’m glad I got to play Brad.<br />
Bad: Brad decides to run against my shadow cuz my Rohan will really clobber his Nazgul.<br />
Ugly: Of all the doubles he could have made, he doubles into the Deep of Helm into 4 fierce minions on his 4 companions. Game.<br />
<br />
Round Two<br />
Steve Miller! With his elf/Gondor – moria archery deck<br />
Result: FW site 9 fellowship win<br />
Good: Steve is mad fun to play against. Always smiling and joking around. <br />
Bad: I feel bad for Steve cuz I got our my two Fortresses in time to get rid of almost all his conditions. <br />
Ugly: Steve never pulls into Gwemegil which he desperately needs for Arwen (the new Arwen would have really killed my shadow good, btw). He really doesn’t get any of his good fellowship support cards until site 7 which makes it too late to beat me to nine.<br />
<br />
Round Three<br />
Michael Ium’s Moria Swarm/ BadBeef (Gimli, Dwarf of Erebor)<br />
Result: FL site 5<br />
Good: I manage to kill Gimli at site 2 with Saruman, SOTE J<br />
Bad: I didn’t draw into ONE companion<br />
Ugly: I simblemyne Brego at site one instead of Firefoot cuz I thought he might be playing Moria Archery and I wanted to heal right away. Big mistake.<br />
<br />
Round Four<br />
Imsham Poolar Moria underdeeps, Gondor-elf<br />
Result: FW Shadow Kill site 5<br />
Good: Imsham never stops making jokes no matter how bad they get<br />
Bad; Man, is it stressful playing against Moria<br />
Ugly: Once again, 4 fierce minions on 4 companions at site 5.<br />
<br />
So Pat and Dom win the tournament and I come in like 3rd or 4th with Tubman, I think. <br />
<br />
At this point, we’re hungry again so we all head off to the Swiss Chalet for chicken, ribs, beer and stuff. We’re quite the group and we end up taking an entire wall of tables. I don’t remember how many of us there were but I think we were about 20. It was pretty fun. At one point, Steve Jones from Syracuse is talking to me and I just ask out loud if anyone wants to trade seats? It was such a good burn. Steve didn’t talk to me for like 5 minutes afterwards. Too funny J   Dom refuses to drink his water cuz he says there’s little pieces of bread in it. That was so funny, I couldn’t even possibly try to explain why.<br />
Swiss Chalet is a BBQ Chicken place which isn’t something I see a lot of in the states. You guys seem to like fried chicken much more. Anyway it is served with this barbeque sauce that you dip the chicken into and stuff, but the Americans that were there were all like, ‘whatever that crap is, it’s ain’t no BBQ sauce.’   It was a rippin’ good time and I’m glad Fuzzy John (Josh’s assistant all weekend) came out to join us. <br />
<br />
Saturday, November 8th, Day One<br />
Abracadabra<br />
<br />
I arrive around 9ish to the place and there is a Second Cup right in front of the venue! Wicked. 15 bucks for parking tho (crap!). I go inside and it has to be the nicest venue I’ve ever seen for a LOTR event. There are windows everywhere and skylights as well. It’s really something else and a perfect environment for serious game play. 35 people show up and Josh decides 6 rounds should do it to pick a top 8 to play in Day Two. Pairings are announced and we’re off!<br />
<br />
Round One<br />
Brad Eire AGAIN but this time with Moria/Ents<br />
We get paired up at the worst possible spot on the table (there’s this big hole right in the middle for the twilight pool to fall thru) so we switch seats (a trend that gains popularity throughout the weekend, especially tomorrow at the Team Tournament)<br />
Result: FL site 9 shadow kill<br />
Good: Brad gets revenge<br />
Bad: I misplay Greenleaf by not getting him killed on purpose at site 5 against Saruman, Black Traitor. By Greenleaf being on the table, I am risking Moria Scouts as well as risking Chief Counsellor when I play Aragorn, ROTN for my 4th culture.<br />
Ugly: So much ugliness went on in our game. I’m just really happy that Brad won cuz there were so many screw ups. I forget, for some reason, that when Frodo dies, only the ring gets transferred to sam and not the frying pan! I’m such a scrub. I really misassigned the minions at site 9 and lost both my ring-bearers. Brad even forgot one of his minions that got mixed up with his fellowship. I hear that having extra minions in a swarm deck is kinda important and should not be forgotten J   <br />
But the REAL screw-up was on Brad’s part at the Cavern Entrance. Let me say first that Brad is the nicest guy ever and a true gentlemen so don’t you all go thinking he’s some sort of idiot for this. But it is pretty darn funny. So I waltz into site 7 Cavern Entrance with Greenleaf, Eowyn, Eomer/Firefoot, Aragorn ROTN and two more companions. Brad plays Orc Insurgent (oh no), Enquea (OH no), Grima Chief Consellor (OH NO) and a ton of moria orcs. He then kills Eowyn with Enquea and pops Eomer and Greenleaf back into my hand. He then proceeds to play Cahadras has not Forgiven Us on my exhausted Aragorn ROTN (defender plus three) but he misplays it cuz now I’m down to four companions. LOL. I end up surviving the site somehow when I should have CLEARLY lost the game. Like I said before, I’m glad Brad won the game in the end. Anything else would have seemed wrong.<br />
<br />
Round Two<br />
Shawn Parker Trackers with the Bon petit fellowship<br />
Result: FW Shadow Kill site 5 (sounds familiar?)<br />
Good: I get out 4 Simblemynes by site 2<br />
Bad: I draw into all 4 Saruman by site 2<br />
Ugly: He doesn’t get his Gandalf out nor does he get any of his awesome weapons that would have really wreaked havoc with my shadow.<br />
<br />
Round Three<br />
Mike Smythe – Nazgul Outwounding – Bon Petit fellowship<br />
Result: Shadow Kill full loss site 9<br />
Good: This was a good match-up for me.<br />
Bad: I made LOTS of mistakes<br />
Ugly: We are both at site 7 and I go first. I move to eight with horses on my guys and I decide it would be smart to exhaust Greenleaf to do more wounds. I then end up losing my skirmishes and if I hadn’t exhausted Greenleaf, the minions would have still been exhausted (thanks to the horses) and I could have shot them at site nine and won. That was the plan. But instead, I exhaust Greenleaf and then MOVE AGAIN with Witch King and another Nazgul still on the table. He then drops two more Nazgul and I die terribly. So not only do I screw up by using Greenleaf on the first move but I MOVE AGAIN. I could totally have stopped him at site 8 and singled into 9 afterwards. Man, I’m glad I won’t be playing this deck much longer. I’m good with the shadow but I really stink at playing Rohan. I think it’ll be back to Dauntless for me soon. (feels like a demotion)<br />
<br />
Lunch break and Dom, Pat and I go to Dunn’s smoked meat across the street where the bartender tells us how his $9,000 magic collection was stolen. Pat decides it’s completely impossible to own $9,000 of Magic cards and I would tend to agree. The bartender also had a nice habit of asking questions and then leaving as you begin to answer them. What the heck?<br />
<br />
Round Four<br />
Matthew Harrison and his Ring Bound rangers-Sam’s Pack / Moria Archery deck<br />
Result: FW shadow Kill site 5 (I’m really going to miss the site 5’s from Two Towers)<br />
Good: Matt is the nicest guy and the calmest player I played all weekend. He’s really young and his Dad came with him and stuck around all day Saturday and Sunday. Matt knows all the cards really well and was really fun to play against. These types of players remind me how amazing this game can be sometimes.<br />
Bad: Did he ever have a bad luck at site 2. I think I killed his entire starting fellowship<br />
Ugly: Sam was alone at site 4 moving into 5 and he gave me 7 twilight. At the deep of helm, that’s enough for Saruman with his Staff and an Uruk Chaser OUCH! BAM!<br />
<br />
I should mention at this point that Malboeuf is taunting me like crazy from the top tables because the scrub tables (where I’ve been playing) are completely separated from the other line of tables so it’s fairly clear where the good players are and where the rest of us are. <br />
<br />
Round Five<br />
Mike Nguliukatukaruck (gosh darnit, I really should have copied the name off the score-card instead of just making it up) and his Rohan/Naz<br />
Result: FW shadow kill site 8<br />
Good: Mike totally rocks and was my favourite opponent at the TOC this year. He was making wicked jokes the entire game<br />
Bad: I, for some reason, didn’t smile at all the entire game. I must have felt really threatened by his deck and was concentrating too much of something. But he had me laughing at the end.<br />
Ugly: He Simblemynes at the same time as getting a horsey with Stables. Thru his fatigue, he completely forgets to get something with Simblemynes but played it anyway. A Rider’s Spear would have really helped his deck at that point.<br />
<br />
Round Six<br />
Luis Chu and his DH-Wingchow / Trackers<br />
Result: FL Shadow Kill site 8<br />
Good: Awesome opponent. I thought that I would have had an advantageous match-up against that fellowship<br />
Bad: I never drew into my companions. I had 8 shadow cards back to back for like 2 or 3 reconciles. It was crazy.<br />
Ugly: the good part about getting just shadow is you get some real fun shadow phases. <br />
<br />
So that’s it. I finish 3-3 YUCK. But I had a real blast. I’m looking forward to never playing this deck again cuz I’m really bad at playing the fellowship. Dominic finishes in first place going undefeated (I think). I’m happy to see that Brad Eire also made it in as well as Malboeuf and Chris Tubman. Should be a good day-two. <br />
<br />
Next up right away is the Sealed Deck Release event for ROTK. We have to be out of the room by 9ish so that only gives us time for three rounds. They aren’t starting for about an hour so Pat, Dom and I hit the local English pub for some quick drinks and food to put us in the right spirits for the tournament. I pound back a pint in no time while Dom gets thru 3 screwdrivers (his first one was a little weak so he specifies for the next one, ‘Dis time wit alcohol please’). The next two screwdrivers are doubles so Dom is feeling pretty good. He says one more should do the trick and Pat and I say no to get back on time. As Pat and I go up the escalators up to the third floor, Dom decides it’ll be fun to go up the wrong escalator (going down) and run up against it. He does this for both floors, tripping the whole time and smashing his knees and palms against the metal steps. By the time he gets to the tournament room he goes right into the middle of the room and collapses from exhaustion. Dom makes another grand entrance.<br />
<br />
I pull the Aragorn starter and get an Easterling Regiment, Rout and Pippin’s Armor (which I, of course, get Pat to sign) as my random rares. YUCK. I decide I should bid one for the entire tournament and try my luck with my deck. Pairings are announced and we’re off…<br />
<br />
Round One<br />
Saul Rothman (Aragorn starter)<br />
Result: TW site 8<br />
Good: I doubled a lot having great courage from a great start. Saul was a really nice opponent and a good sport.<br />
Bad: I double into site 6 with 7 threats and Saul plays the WitchKing. His game text says that my Ring-bearer can’t take threat wounds. I think I had like 9 companions or something going into site 6 and I left with 3 or 4. OUCH.<br />
Ugly: Timed games suck. I think I would have won anyway but I hate it when time runs out. I guess it’s to be expected with both him and I are reading every single card we draw and play.<br />
<br />
I can’t remember if it was round one or two but beside me, Malboeuf was playing Brash(sp?) who’s this big nice guy that had played Dom the day before. I don’t know how new Brash is to the game but he’s certainly less polished a player than Malboeuf. Anyway their game goes to time as well with Malboeuf at site 8 and Brash at site 6. Josh comes over and asks what the outcome would probably be? Malboeuf says he’s obviously going to win cuz he has 7 companions at site 8 and will single into 9 next turn. Brash then responds that they wouldn’t be in this predicament if Malboeuf hadn’t taken so long in the assignment phases earlier on. Now let me say that I’ve NEVER seen someone be able to get to Malboeuf and get him to lose his cool but Brash, God bless him, pulled it off. So after Brash kinda accuses Malboeuf of stalling, Pat gets up and says loudly (try to imagine this in the French-Canadian accent) ‘C’MON MAN! WHAT ARE YOU TALKING BOUT, MAN?’ I almost died laughing right there. <br />
<br />
Round Two<br />
Imshan Poolar ‘Aragorn starter’<br />
Result: Full loss site 9 fellowship win for him<br />
Good: Imshan was really good at playing the Aragorn starter. He knew all the cards by heart already and it taught me how I should be playing my deck.<br />
Bad: I’m at 7 companions the entire time but because of my bad experience with the Witch-King in my previous game, I’ve been conditioned to become scared of doubling so I let Imshan take the lead and win the race out of fear.<br />
Ugly: At site two, Imshan tells me ‘I don’t want to sound like a jerk, but could you please hurry up’ cuz I’m reading the cards. Dude, I’ve never seen the dang cards before in my life. I didn’t read the entire spoiler list like you did. The funniest thing about that is that he said this after about 5 seconds of me reading my fellowship cards. It’s not like I took 10 minutes or anything. <br />
<br />
So what happens in this round with Brash is almost even funnier. Dom (of ALL people) gets paired up with Brash right after the Malboeuf match. Dom decides, for fun, that he is going to bid 9 and start Smeagol. Then when Brash tells Dom he’s lost the game by going to 10 burdens, Dom’s plan is to go ballistic and call over the judge and fight it (even though he plans on conceding the game right away). It’s actually quite a funny plan on paper. Brash will get the full win and Dom will get to have fun yelling at Josh that the ruling isn’t fair cuz he’s been drinking or something. BUT the plan goes terribly wrong and Brash ends up bidding TEN cuz he doesn’t want to play Dom. So Dom gets the full win even though he wanted the full loss. Dom felt really bad about it the next day and apologized to Brash (what a sweetie). <br />
<br />
So after two rounds, Pat, myself and Dom all agree that this is the most boring tournament we’ve ever played in our entire lives. The starter decks ARE SO DULL and we’re all sleepy and want to go and do more fun stuff but there’s only one more round so instead of dropping, we continue.<br />
<br />
Round Three<br />
Steve Jones!!!  ‘Aragorn starter’<br />
Result: TW site 8<br />
Good: I’m so happy I didn’t drop cuz now I get to play Steve who is SO FUNNY. Steve’s my buddy from Syracuse so when we each present each other our decks for cutting, I tap on Steve’s deck as a sign of trust and he grabs mine and makes this face that I could only describe as ‘rubbing it in my face’ and cuts my deck in slow motion. It was really funny.<br />
Bad: I hate timed games.<br />
Ugly: I got to Red Wrath away like 2 or 3 of Steve’s companions and always when there were threats on the table. Everytime I did it, I would bend my index finger and start chanting RED WRATH RED WRATH (just like that little freak in the Shining) and then put two wounds on the character and slide my Red Wrath underneath his companion who is about to die and flip the card straight up so that the wound tokens smash Steve in the face. It was so funny, I almost died. By the third companion, I was getting real good at aiming and I send the card and one token right into Steve’s forehead and eye while the other token slammed into a neighboring player’s ear. Man, it was funny.<br />
<br />
So I finish 2-1 and win the random scrub give-away T-shirt that says WIZARD on the front. Where in the world am I going to WEAR THIS? I can get away with wearing the one that says Ring-Bound (thanks to Peter Sundholm for giving me the tip that when people ask what that means, you reply, I’m married) and the shirt that says Fierce generally makes people just walk away. But there is no way I can get away with wearing a t-shirt that says Wizard unless I’ve got some sort of Klu Klux Klan hood on (and then I’d be opening a whole other jar of worms). <br />
<br />
So ends a really long day and unfortunately, no plans had been hammered out as to what everyone wants to do so people just sort of go their separate ways and I’m all pissed cuz I was hoping we’d all go out drinking together or, at the very least, go for a bite to eat. So as the group splits and splits again, I have to decide who I want to stick with. Well the decision really isn’t that tough. I know the 4 guys from Syracuse are cool as hell so I jump with their pack and head back to their hotel to hear hilarious stories about how Steve Jones snores and wakes everyone up while Josh P. is trying to sleep. <br />
<br />
The five of us end up going to Gretsky’s (am I a bad Canadian for not knowing how to spell the bastard’s name?) for supper and have a great time. Steve, Josh and I exchange stories on New York city and stuff while I pound away a couple single-malt scotches (Glenlivet rocks). The waitress, Lindsay is being a big phonie-baloney with us and calling Josh by his first name and everything just to get the bigger tip, but it doesn’t bother us much cuz her shirt is missing many buttons and stuff. But unfortunately I can never look cuz she never breaks eye contact with me. So while the other 4 guys get a good luck, I gotta pretend to be nice and everything. Anyway we’re debating what to order, and Josh goes for the surf and turf for like 30 bucks. It ends up being the smallest, most pitiful serving I’ve ever seen. I feel bad for Josh. I’m wondering what to order and then remember that we’re driving back tomorrow and I need to exact my revenge on Pat and Dom for their biological warfare they bestowed upon me after the Pizza Hut lunch. So I order the meatloaf and garlic mashed potatoes and never look back.<br />
<br />
The evening wraps up and I head over to my uncle’s to crash and think about perhaps winning a game or two at the Team Tournament (I really should have brought more than one deck).<br />
<br />
Sunday, November 9th, Day Two<br />
‘Biological Warfare and cumshots’<br />
<br />
So I sleep in really late since I don’t have to be there for 9am for Day Two. Team tournament only starts at noon. I arrive around 11 and see Malboeuf about to eliminate Brad Eire already. He kinda tricked him into double moving to site 3 and then getting mobbed by bunch of Dunlendings. It’s so weird that situation presented itself cuz half the drive down, we were discussing how to fool an opponent into double moving without showing him you really want him to. Looks like Malboeuf figured it out. Brad Eire is the first eliminated and I try to recruit him into my Team (I brought CardShark t-shirts for most of my members so we look a little more intimidating). But Brad had to go home early. Darn. So I recruit Steve Miller, Malcolm Daligesh and the money-pick, Dan Clark. I have t-shirts for Steve and Malcolm and I give Dan the shark move token that Malboeuf uses for luck. We look like a pretty solid team and we’re anxious to see if we can pull it off.<br />
<br />
I should mention that the room we are playing in is less than half the size of the previous day’s room and it’s real hell trying to play games on skinny tables. I end up reserving a round table for all of my games with my teammate, Steve Miller, on the other end. However, I’m surprised he wants to be near me because the meatloaf I had the night before with the garlic mashed potatoes has caught up with me and has given me the WORST gas I’ve ever had in my life. I let a fresh one go and holy crap, did the air density ever change. It was like half spoiled meat and half really good cheese. There were these two kids trading cards at the table near me and they both got up in a flash and moved to the other end of the room. But the best was that I was right in the middle of Team ‘Cuse and they scatter for the windows and started banging on the glass all frantic-like. Man, it was hilarious. But Malboeuf’s reaction had to be the funniest cuz it was meant for him and he knew it. <br />
<br />
Round One<br />
Brendan Giles<br />
Ents/Sauron Swarm<br />
Result: FW site 9 shadow kill<br />
Good: It was my first time ever playing against this type of deck so it was very refreshing. I know Sauron Swarm really well cuz I play them in Towers Block so I was prepared for all the tricks.<br />
Bad: He gives me 30 pool at site 2 and I have One uruk in hand.<br />
Ugly: At site 4, I play an Uruk Hunter with Saruman SOTE. I exert to put him on Merry. He prevents. I do it again cuz Merry is exhausted. I kill merry (since he can’t discard him) and then exert my Hunter Twice to exhaust Pippin and then exert Saruman to put the Hunter on Pippin, killing him too!!! : <br />
<br />
Malcolm Daligesh is the only other member of my team that wins first round.<br />
<br />
Round Two<br />
Michael Ium<br />
Underdeeps, Badbeef<br />
Result: FL site 7<br />
Good: I killed his ENTIRE fellowship (including Gimli at site 2 again)<br />
Bad: He always had a severed his bonds to keep Frodo alive<br />
Ugly: Cavern Entrance sucks so hard<br />
<br />
This time, Steve and Dan win their games and Malcolm loses.<br />
<br />
Round 3<br />
BRASH! <br />
Battleground Uruks, Rohan<br />
Result: FW site 9 fellowship<br />
Good: This is the last time I’ll ever have to play against those pesky Battleground uruks<br />
Bad: He made a few mistakes all game long which I allowed takebacks but at site 8, he really messed up and I think he could have killed me so I ceased the takebacks and it threw him off. He plays Pillage of Rohan which is going to KILL my fellowship since I have a Fortress Never Fallen with 8 tokens on it, We Left None Alive, Arrow Slits and THREE Thundering Hosts. So he plays like 4 Uruks at once and then tells me to get rid of my conditions. I tell him he has to do it one at a time and he agrees and looks at his hand again. He forgets that he can still nail one of my conditions with the last Uruk he played and instead plays ANOTHER uruk and places a token on Attack on helm’s Deep and then tells me to get rid of my Fortress. I don’t even have to open my mouth before he realizes that he can either do Attack on Helm’s Deep OR Pillage of Rohan. Not both. Anyway it was a good learning experience for him and I don’t think he’ll ever make that mistake again.<br />
Ugly: He plays 3 uruks at site 6 Caves. Two are big and one is small. I thought they were all the same so I make Aragorn defender plus 2 and Sam defender plus one and sacrifice my companions. However the small strength 8 uruk who Eomer could have killed easily ends up being the one where when a companion dies, he controls a site. So because of my negligence, Brash grabs two sites and makes the next three sites a living hell for my fellowship. He got me good on that one. <br />
<br />
Dan Clark is the only other member of my team to win a game in this round.<br />
<br />
Round 4<br />
Steve Jones!!!<br />
DH-WingCHOW / Truckers<br />
Result: FW site 9<br />
Good: Steve ROCKS. I was making Perfect choices of double moves this game and felt very confident against his fellowship.<br />
Bad: At site 5 I lose some companions and don’t draw into anymore until site 7. So for two sites I am walking around with 3 companions only. Ouch. <br />
Ugly: Vengeance?! What the heck? I can’t remember playing with that card ever. I lost some companions cuz of that and made me very scared to block with Frodo. Those Uruk Plains Runners are a pain in the butt. Frodo had to keep blocking and I was up to 6 burdens in no time. I had to make a big decision at site 5 where either my Elite Rider dies or I risk Frodo. I ended up picking the latter and that single decision was my game-winning move. If I had lost the Elite Rider, Frodo would not have survived site 7 (since I didn’t draw into any fresh companions)<br />
<br />
Both Dan and Malcolm win their games as well. Steve Miller is apparently our heavy anchor J<br />
<br />
Round 5<br />
Canaan Chu<br />
Nazgul/ Rohan-Gandalf<br />
Result: Full loss site 9<br />
Good: It was a very well played match. Toughest match-up of the weekend for me.<br />
Bad: Canaan is debating what to play at site 6 (he has some extra companions in hand). He is apparently debating if flooding the pool is a good idea or not. His teammate, Michael is standing behind me looking at my hand which comprises no less than EIGHT shadow cards. Michael then moseys on over behind Canaan, bends over beside him and says one word, ‘choke.’     DUDE, WTF? I’m sitting right in front of you! I’ve never seen such an obvious cheat made in my life. Coaching is totally illegal dude, what are you thinking?! So I’m debating if I should call a judge but Canaan ends up flooding the pool and dumping his hand so he didn’t follow his teammate’s advice or anything so I didn’t bother. Plus, it,s just a dumb team tournament and not for cash so what’s the big deal right?<br />
Ugly: Canaan doubles into site 9 and I am left with the TOUGHEST decision of all weekend as to which Saruman to fetch. I have Enquea who will kill a companion leaving him at 5 companions. Saruman, Black Traitor will be an extra minion which could really help. But Servant of the Eye is always the right choice for site 9. I really can’t decide. His fellowship is in REAL good shape so Servant of the Eye won’t do me much good I think, so I elect for an additional minion. In the maneuver phase, he roll of thunder’s my Saruman’s Staff so Black Traitor is totally useless. No way to win this situation. <br />
<br />
In the final round, all three of my teammates win their games except me. <br />
So Dan Clark goes 4-1!<br />
Malcolm and myself go 3-2 and Steve goes 2-3.<br />
<br />
In the end, our Team wins the whole thing! We end up drafting the Anthology and each get two Towers boosters. <br />
<br />
Dom, Pat and I jump into the car and head back to Montreal. We stop at a Swiss Chalet on the way back where all we do is laugh for a good hour about a ton of stuff and get back to Montreal at 2 in the morning with Work at 8. Dom was kind enough to give us a bunch of cumshot stories to help pass the time on the drive home. I had trouble falling asleep that night…<br />
<br />
Props:<br />
·	Pat Malboeuf for winning the whole thing and for being the best traveling partner ever<br />
·	Dom for being funny as hell and for drinking with me Saturday before the sealed deck boring event<br />
·	Steve Jones for being a good buddy and being quite tolerant of my non-stop jokes at his expense. Gretsky’s was really fun, man. Glad we made it out together. Also thanks VERY much for the box.<br />
·	Chris Tubman for his great attitude and for coming all the way just to have a good time. I’m thinking I gotta give you slops tho for not coming out with us Saturday night<br />
·	Josh Cornwall-Mott for pulling off a flawless event. Fantastic organizing and you smiled the entire time. Wicked. <br />
·	Josh P. for laughing it up with us Saturday night as well and for not getting pissed at me saying no everytime you wanted to have a casual game<br />
·	Fuzzy John for helping out organizing the event but especially for those really kind words he gave me at the end of the Team event. He told me of all the ‘big’ players, I’m the nicest and especially kind with new players that need guidance and a little bit of shared wisdom to get them on the right track. For a while there, I feel like I had lost my way and it’s really great to be reminded of who I am and what effect I have on most people. Thanks a lot, man.<br />
·	Brash for actually making Malboeuf lose his cool. I don’t know how you did it but I’m certainly going to try and emulate whatever you did. Also I like how you accept the fact that you make huge mistakes in games so that you’ll learn to not do them again. In Montreal, we have some local players that continuous make the silliest mistakes (Bernatchez comes to mind) but don’t accept the fact that they are making mistakes and get takebacks and then will never improve as a player. Brash, you’re totally going to get better by continuously making dumb mistakes (like we all used to back in the day). Look forward to our next match.<br />
·	Brad Eire for smiling the ENTIRE weekend. Our two games were really fun<br />
·	Steve Miller for being a great friend throughout the weekend. Never mind that you totally anchored the team on Sunday J  If you had lost one more game, we wouldn’t have won, so you totally contributed. Glad we got to hang out.<br />
·	Mike Smythe for beating me in a game where I really should have won. You played really well, man.<br />
·	Dan Clark for being a great guy and always having a positive attitude. Also you’re the ONLY reason our team won the tournament. Thanks, man. Can’t wait to see you around this summer.<br />
·	Matthew Harrison for being my favourite player there. It’s SO COOL that you won so many games. You’ve got some serious potential. Keep playing and keep making your dad drive you to big tournaments J<br />
·	Mike Nguluck for getting me a box that had a foil ring in it. Also thanks for always making jokes in your games and keeping LOTR fun and friendly. SO important.<br />
·	Malcolm Daligesh for wrestling me right to the ground and embarrassing me in front of everybody. Also thanks for being on our team and kicking butt.<br />
·	Julien Daligesh for being the cutest LOTR player ever (even tho you don’t play anymore). You need to come to more events, man. Montreal!!! You only need to be 18 to drink!<br />
·	Malcolm and any others that get my Family Guy references. I was so impressed that Malcolm knew what I was doing when I smashed my knee during the wrestling. That was hilarious.<br />
·	Brian MacDonald, Steven Sy, Noah M and the other guy and girls that came all the way from Ottawa to play. You guys are so awesome.<br />
<br />
And now for my fun slops:<br />
·	Imshan Poolar for making our games more of a chore than an actual challenge or fun experience.<br />
·	Michael Ium for telling your teammate, Canaan to CHOKE when you saw I was holding 8 shadow cards. Dude, don’t ever do that again. You’re much too nice a guy to do crap like that.<br />
·	Malcolm for being the reason his brother doesn’t play cards anymore.<br />
·	Dom for embarrassing me when he asks the waitress to put alcohol into his screwdriver the next time around<br />
·	Dom for embarrassing me when he asks the waitress to not put any bread into his water<br />
·	Dom for embarrassing me when the waitress asks him if he wants his apple pie heated and he responds ‘yes, to eat.’   (misunderstanding ‘heat’ for ‘eat) too funny<br />
·	Me for dropping spoiled-meat farts in a really small room full of people<br />
·	Whoever that gamer was that smelled like spoiled meat and cheese the entire weekend (it wasn’t me, by the way)<br />
<br />
That about covers it. If you want to read a better TR, check out Chris Tubman’s version. It is totally hilarious. <br />
<br />
And if you want to come to an event that’ll be just as much fun as this, make sure to come to Montreal, Quebec, Canada the second weekend in January for a big weekend of LOTR events being held in a BAR!!! Foil ring, cash and other great prizes… Ask me or Yako for details.<br />
